{
  "text": "Different solutions to minimum cost flow for MOT have been proposed recently. In [CITATION_1] a global optimal solution is found using push-relabel algorithm. Pirsiavash et al. in [CITATION_2] utilize the same graph as [CITATION_3] , and solve the problem using a fast greedy shortest path procedure based on dynamic programming. Berclaz et al. in [CITATION_4] introduce an efficient shortest path algorithm to solve the flow problem. In [CITATION_5] , a new network flow is proposed to incorporate constant velocity motion model in the graph and the solution is found efficiently using Lagrange relaxation. Shitrit et al. [CITATION_6] (top row). A pre-trained object detector fails when objects go under heavy articulation. This error is propagated to the data association step, which consequently cause failure in tracking. Differently, our method is based on online discriminative learning and solves detection and global data association simultaneously, thus handles articulated targets well. The same observation can be made from (b). Each row represents one of the three identities in the scene. Each circle shows a corresponding match in a frame and the color represents the ID that is assigned to that detection.",
  "citation_candidates": [
